Another misogynistic 'war' offering from JP Dutta. Even when he did try to do a woman based film-it was a disaster..this is the man who very naively thought it was a good idea to mess about making a remake of a classic that can never be beaten by the original ...Umrao Jaan! There are classics in Hindi cinema that should never be messed with - Mughal-e-Azam, Pakeezah, Mother India, Sholay(Ram Gopal Verma's stupidity) and Umrao Jaan. So I predict another flop when this one is released. Jai Hind.

Very very nice movie. Just watched it. You can feel every punch, every dialogue, every bullet. Very well-directed and realistic. This is JP Dutta's second best after Border, although from a perspective of realistic direction, this is his best I feel. Border had more masala, but this one is more realistic and also includes the mind games that soldiers play on the battlefield. The songs are also good - Paltan Ho Paltan, Raat Kitni and Main Zinda Hoon. One of Anu Malik's best albums. Everyone acted well, Arjun, Sonu and Jackie. Harshvardhan Rane and Gurmeet were particularly good. The last 30 minutes of war scenes were nail biting. I would request everyone to go and watch this movie. We need these kinds of movies to work at the BO. Salute to the '67 platoon that saved India and salute the team that made this movie. After a long time I watched something that moved me.

While Paltan is the story of the '67 battle, the '62 one was no less when it comes to bravery. On November 18, 1962, on the snow-clad mountains of Chushul in Ladakh, took place the battle that is still considered to be one of the greatest last stands in the history of armed forces across the world.

The Charlie company of 120 jawans of 13 Kumaon led by Major Shaitan Singh was protecting Chushul airfield which was vital if India had to hold on to Ladakh.

The attack started at 03:30 in morning and soon Chushul got enveloped by heavy firing from Chinese. But the Indian soldier didnâ€™t give up and kept retaliating with whatever means they had.

A lesser army might have retreated, but the company led by commander Major Shaitan Singh fought till last man, last round, and last breath. Legend says that the brave 120 killed close to 1,300 enemy soldiers. Only 6 of the 120 member company survived the war, 114 did not.

The remaining six were taken as Prisoners of War (POW) by Chinese, but all miraculously escaped. Out of these six heroes, only four are alive now.

Major Shaitan Singh who was later awarded Parma Vir Chakra (PVR) for leading the company and showing valour beyond imagine always knew that they were fighting a lost battle. But he refused to surrender and led his men with unparalleled valour. The company was also awarded five Vir Chakras, and four Sena medals apart from the PVC awarded to the commander.

India hasnâ€™t lost a lot of wars â€“ which is why 1962 India-China war is essential because it hardened the resolve for India to create an army like no other.

Despite the fact that India lost the war, it made us realise how important it was to modernise our army and weaponry. The only thing that stood out though was the bravado of the Indian soldier - who fought to his last breath without weapons or back up often with his bare hands like in the case of Rezang La.

One such story was the legend of Jaswant Singh, the man who saved Arunachal Pradesh from the Chinese. Legend says he himself killed 300 Chinese Soldiers. 

Sources: 

https://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/44-years-ago-120-men-saved-ladakh-from-china-this-is-the-story-of-the-greatest-last-stand-ever-at-rezang-la-252749.html
https://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/the-heroic-story-of-jaswant-singh-the-man-who-saved-arunachal-pradesh-from-the-chinese-army-247929.html

And the world knows how Indians defeated the Chinese in 1967. Thereafter, by God's grace and the valor of our soldiers, we have lost no major wars.

3. COMPLETELY wrong weaponry shown. Indian troops had 1A1 SLRs,  NOT .303s!!. 
4. WHY THE HELL are Indian officers all wearing caps?? They would either wear their helmets in combat or a beret otherwise.
Seriously, very very shoddy  B-GRADE WORK. I hope somebody in India starts making proper war films. Lost all hope in JP Dutta.

It seems that, jp dutta has forgotten that it  is  2018.

1962 war wasn't because of China. It was because India under Nehru and Krishna Menon's forward March ideas made China attack India. China gave India dozens of warnings not to move forward from the actual LAC. Even then Army generals warned Nehru and Mennon about it's consequences. But those men in power insisted and kept taking land and increasing the Indian border by several hundred kilometers.
And when China finally lost it's cool and attacked India, they captured till Tezpur in Assam which is deep into the Indian territory. Nehru like a coward wished well on the AIR to the Northeast front. This is where the seed of hatered towards the Indian government started and gave rise to militant groups like the infamous ULFA. 
Nehru and Mennon were wolves in sheep's skin. They were the one came up with Hindi chini Bhai Bhai and had imperialistic approach by the back door.
And the loss was taken by the then brave Indian soldiers who were ill equipped, but Nehru on the radio boasted and lied to the Indian population of a well equipped strong army. India could've even pushed back China till the winters by using the Indian Air Force (at that time the IAF was stronger than the PLAF) but again the cowardice act of Nehru who feared that the PLA had a better Air support too, led to the death of several hundreds more.
The army didn't had winter clothes, no proper food. In a particular incident the Indian army's ration was in such a poor condition that an officer had to write letter on a chapati to the HQ. He had to face court martial for that action. Such irony.
